COPY public.hib_checklist (id, user_id, hib_section, hib_clause, hib_clause_description, implementation_status, remarks, additional_information_i, additional_information_ii, additional_information_iii, created_at, updated_at, section_number, suggested_artefacts) FROM stdin;
0d783288-e506-4a17-899f-5fa4e840cb96	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	5	Anti-malware solutions shall be configured to auto-update signature files or equivalent (e.g., non-signature-based machine learning solutions) to detect new malware. Where possible, signature updates should take place at least daily to stay protected from the latest malware.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2	
46bc1dab-7428-4b6e-80a5-ab1903749719	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	6	Anti-malware solutions shall be configured to automatically scan the files upon access. This includes files and attachments downloaded from the Internet through the web browser or email, and external sources such as from portable USB drives.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2	
20b95ed1-3e9e-44f0-b69f-e5c97b0779cb	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	7	Firewalls shall be deployed or switched on to protect the network, systems, and endpoints such as laptops, desktops, and servers	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2	The organization shall protect their network with firewalls, including for devices such as but not limited to endpoints, personal computers, servers and BYOD.\nFirewalls include:\na) Network firewall\nFor protecting the network from unauthorised network traffic.\nExample: F5 or Cisco firewall\nb) Host based firewall\nFor protection of operating systems for endpoints and servers, etc.\nExample: Microsoft Defender or Symantec Endpoint Protection
3c4a9b7e-8178-48af-8c97-5ef04a1da6f4	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	3	Anti-malware solutions shall be used and installed in endpoints to detect attacks on the healthcare provider�s environment. Examples of endpoints include laptops, desktops, and servers.	Yes		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-06-03 06:39:58.315497+00	2	1. The organisation shall implement an anti-malware solution and the solution should be centrally managed.\nTo ensure support for the anti-malware solution, Commercial-off-the-shelf (COTS) solutions shall be used and continually subscribed in order to get update and patches.\n2. The organisation should consider implementing advanced anti-malware solutions such as Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR) and Advanced Threat Protection solutions for a more adequate and enhanced protection.\nSuch protection should cover services or solution such as FTP, email and any downloads to end user computing device, servers and personal devices that interact with provider(s) system or network. This should include OT or IoT devices/network.\n3. The anti-malware solution shall be installed at all endpoints (including but not limited to personal computers, servers BYOD and IoT) to protect the devices from viruses and malware
6fe665f9-5ebb-4695-93e5-1a47edd1c8f9	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	4	Virus and malware scans shall be carried out to detect possible attacks. Where feasible, scans should always be automated and remain active to provide constant protection.	Yes		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-06-03 06:40:01.292761+00	2	1. The anti-malware solution shall be configured to:\na) be in an active state;\nb) conduct scheduled scans of the system;\nc) ensure live definition updates are automatically turned on;\nd) prevent users from changing the configuration and turning off or uninstalling the solution.\ne) active scanning shall be turned on to protect files and attachments from services or solutions such as but not limited to FTP, email to or any downloads to the endpoints including OT or IoT devices/network.\n2. When determining the frequency and timing of the scheduled scan, the organisation should consider the impact of the scanning on system resources and to schedule the timing of the scans accordingly. Where possible, signature updates should take place at least daily to stay continue protected from the latest malware.\n3. The organisation shall review the anti-malware report regularly to follow-up
79e9fdd3-6edd-4550-aefb-7d6bf23fe69e	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	8	A network perimeter firewall shall be configured to analyse and accept only authorised network traffic into the healthcare provider�s network (e.g., a Local Area Network (LAN) made up of a group of computers or devices in the same physical location connected over a network). Examples could include packet filter, Domain Name System (DNS) firewall and application-level gateway firewall with rules to restrict and filter network traffic. Depending on the healthcare provider�s network setup, the firewall functionality may be integrated with other networking devices, or as a standalone device.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2	1. Firewalls shall be configured to only allow legitimate traffic to be transmitted. Firewall rules such as �Any to Any� shall be disallowed.\n2. The firewall rules shall be:\na) reviewed on a periodic basis such as at minimally half yearly.\nb) removed when no longer required.\nc) clearly documented and approved by appropriate management personnel.
ec9bcd86-d5af-4a91-86df-d820bc56bc39	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	9	The healthcare provider shall ensure its employees install or access only authorised software or attachments from official or trusted sources. This requirement may be met in different ways, e.g., install an application control solution that is integrated with antivirus software that uses both whitelisting and blacklisting to prevent unauthorised applications (including malware) from running. The whitelist takes reference from the list of healthcare provider�s authorised assets and review the list of blocked applications from the application control solution and remove all unnecessary applications.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2	1. An authorised software list shall be established for software that is allowed installation onto a corporate device.\n2. An authorisation process to review software for onboarding should be established.\n3. Use of freeware or third-party software that are not approved by management should hence not allowed to be installed.\nOnly authorised software or attachments from official or trusted sources shall be installed or accessed. "Official or trusted sources" refer to reputable and reliable channels from which software or attachments can be obtained or accessed safely.\nExamples include:\nOfficial Websites\nThe primary website of the software developer or vendor, where users can download software or attachments directly. These websites often have mechanisms to verify the authenticity of the software and provide support to users.\nApp Stores\nPlatforms like Apple's App Store, Google Play Store, or Microsoft Store are considered official sources for downloading software applications for their respective operating systems. These platforms vet applications for security and quality before making them available to users.\n4. Organisation shall conduct a check annually at minimum or at a frequency determined by Management to ensure compliance and licensing requirements are met.
dcb36c02-fef4-49cf-87ed-8a67da00e5f3	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	10	The healthcare provider shall ensure employees use trusted network connections (e.g., mobile hotspot, personal Wi-Fi, corporate Wi-Fi, and Virtual Private Network (VPN)) for accessing the healthcare provider�s data or business email as opposed to the use of publicly available network connections.\n\nThe healthcare provider shall also educate employees of the risks of using publicly available network connections, which are highly accessible and vulnerable against cyber-attacks (e.g., spoofing attacks that set\nup fake access points to look like Wi-Fi connections for gaining access to a system or stealing information).	No		No		CSA website on Cybersecurity Toolkits (details of trusted network):	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2	Trusted network refers to the users when using the network are aware of the provider of the network and assurance has been obtained that it is safe for use.\n1. A Virtual Private Network (VPN) shall be implemented to ensure a trusted network connection for any remote access.\n2. For employees who connect via BYOD to access corporate network remotely, such devices shall correspondingly be installed with a Mobile Device Management (MDM) solution to ensure trusted connection.\nThere shall be containerization+ of corporate data and the ability to disable the extraction of data through copying or screen-capture of the data by the BYOD owner.\n+Containerization refers to the process of segregating personal and corporate data on personal devices by creating a logical container/separate space to enhance corporate data security.\n3. Organisation shall include policy requirements, best practices such as danger of using public wireless network as part of Cyber Security awareness and new employee on-boarding process and educat employees on the risks of using untrusted networks
321584ae-6a11-4ec9-81fa-2afa02480008	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[2]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Use anti-malware & anti-virus solutions to protect against malicious software	11	The healthcare provider shall ensure its employees are aware of the need to report any suspicious email or attachment to the IT team and / or senior management immediately.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2	Organisation shall communicate and make available the workflow on the immediate reporting of suspicious email/activities to its IT team or senior management.\nExample:\nThe organisation could establish an IT security mailbox or incident hotline for staff to report suspicious IT activities.
1be3ec57-77bf-40e0-8d0e-e7cecef5a7fe	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	12	Healthcare providers shall have a system of account management to maintain\nand manage the inventory of accounts. This requirement may be met in different ways, e.g., using a spreadsheet, exporting the list from the software directory service.	No		No		Sample Account Management / Access\nControl Policy	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	Organisation shall maintain an inventory listing of all access accounts either via a system or using spreadsheets.\nNote: When using a spreadsheet, organisation needs to ensure secure storage and protection of the spreadsheet from tampering and unauthorized access.
bd1bd23f-47f2-419f-98b8-a1ac84391619	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	13	The account inventory list shall contain minimally the following details, for the user,\nadministrator, third-party, and service accounts:\ni. Name;\nii. Username;\niii. Department;\niv. Role/Account Type;\nv. Date of access created; and\nvi. Last log-on date	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. The account inventory list shall be reviewed on a regular basis such\nas half yearly or annually and when there are changes in the organisational structure to prevent the misuse of the account and account privileges.\nThe frequency of the review shall be assessed based on operational requirements and risk and shall be approved by management and documented.\n2. The account inventory list shall be updated whenever there is a change in:\na) staff movement such as new joiner, leaver or a change in department or job roles\nb) systems or applications such as new systems or system decommissioning\nc) access rights or roles for the account
0351a2c7-3d3f-435a-9d7b-66ac030cfbc2	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	14	The healthcare provider shall have a process to grant and revoke access only\nwhen the appropriate approvals are granted. This requirement may be implemented in different ways, e.g., email approval, or access request form. Approvals for any change in access to devices or applications shall be sought when there are personnel changes such as onboarding of new staff or change of role for employees. The following fields shall be captured for staff who are\ngranted access to accounts:\ni. Name;\nii. System to access;\niii. Department;\niv. Role/Account type;\nv. From date; and\nvi. To date	No		No		Sample Access Control Policy	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. The organisation shall establish a process to review all accounts and account privileges on a regular basis such as at a minimum half yearly basis.\n2. The review process shall include the following:\na) verification of the need to maintain the account and/or access rights with the assigned access rights reviewer (such as Reporting Officer, Head of Department or Management)\nb) verify inactive users and accounts and/or access rights\n3. Access control practices shall include:\na) approvals for any new accounts\nb) Disable accounts when user is away\nc) Revoke inactive accounts or access rights immediately\nAn inactive ID refers to a prolong period where the account is not use or no transaction continuously up to X days as agreed by Management (example of X=90 days). Organisation should review the operational requirement and risk prior to defining the review period or X and this shall be documented.
8b730274-3b8c-4904-91c5-5939b4c72c99	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	15	Access shall be managed to ensure that employees can access only the information and systems required for their job role	No		No		Sample Roles & Permission Matrix	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisation shall maintain a user access matrix (UAM), documenting the access rights of the individual and applications.
904a4f25-a07c-4fb3-becb-c0038eb7abd3	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	24	Two-factor authentication (2FA) shall be used for administrative access (including remote access) to important systems, such as an Internet-facing system containing sensitive or business-critical data. This requirement may be implemented in different ways, e.g., use of an authenticator application on the mobile or one-time password (OTP) token	No		No		Information Security Classification Framework	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisation shall put in place a matrix to determine system classifications according to the impact and significance of the system in nature.\n2. Access to systems that are deemed critical to business operations and/or contain sensitive data shall be enforced with 2-factor authentication.\n\nExample of 2FA includes authentication program Microsoft Authenticator on mobile device or One time password (OTP).\n\nNote: A system classification matrix should take into consideration the impact to the organisation based on the following:\nData sensitivity\nInternet facing\nSystem that has impact to patient record and patient care
9fc34f1e-8661-4838-829b-d45c5b95036f	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	16	Accounts with access rights that are no longer required, or have exceeded the requested date, shall have their access disabled, or removed from the system upon a periodic review of the access rights of all accounts. Shared, duplicate, obsolete, and invalid accounts shall be removed (frequency depends on a healthcare provider's operating needs and circumstances). For example, this can include reviewing the privileges required for all accounts and give users, other than the administrator, the least user privileges necessary to carry out his / her work. Similar access rights reviews shall be conducted for access to health information.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisations shall grant user access based on the principle of least privilege where users or systems are granted the minimum rights and authorizations that they require to perform their functions.\n2. Organisation shall establish a process to record user access requests and approvals and monitor such requests to ensure accounts and access rights are correctly granted.\n3. User access reviews shall be conducted regularly, and accounts / access rights are removed if:\na) no longer required\nb) exceeded requested date\nc) if is a shared account\nd) is a duplicate account\ne) is obsolete\nf) is invalid
e174a462-c3b2-42cb-8eb0-3bb8ebfc6c91	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	17	The administrator account shall only be accessed to perform administrator functions with approval from the senior management. Staff with administrator privileges should only use it when required, and regularly review user privileges according to the scope of the user in the institution.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisation shall establish a governance process to manage the use of administrative accounts.\n2. Usage of administrative accounts shall require appropriate approvals by senior management prior to usage.\n3. Each usage is required to be logged (e.g., via email or logbook), maintained and reviewed on a regular basis, such as at minimum quarterly.\n4. Any unusual activities shall be investigated and reported to senior management.
916fdb36-0702-4782-86fe-bb89fbcd22a7	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	18	Account password shall be changed in the event of any suspected compromise or lost tokens. Healthcare providers should also ensure that staff do not share passwords or tokens.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	Organisation shall put in place procedures to ensure that passwords of accounts suspected to have compromised is to be changed immediately.\n\nExample:\nInform user with compromised account to change password immediately or enforced change password upon next logon at system level.
ab703d90-3bc0-4dd5-bdc4-bdc082a73adb	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	19	Healthcare providers shall ensure that all default passwords are replaced with a strong passphrase. A strong passphrase is usually at least 12 characters long and include upper case, lower case, and/or special characters. In setting passwords, publicly known information, or predictable character combinations (e.g., �password�, �qwerty� or �ABC�) shall be avoided.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisation shall replace all system account default passwords with a new password immediately before system goes live.\n2. Organisation shall use passphrase as the default password configuration.\n\nExample of a passphrase: Ilov3myCurry@westside\n\nGuidelines for creating strong password/passphrase:\na) Password minimum length should be 12 character long and shall include 3 of the 4 below combination: of upper cap, lower cap, number or special characters.
07b820a5-8c27-43de-b8c6-b993f6023804	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	20	Healthcare providers shall not use the same password to encrypt all electronic storage mediums or computer devices (e.g., setting one password across the board for all accounts).	No		No		Sample Passphrase Policy Guide from CIS	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisation shall ensure that the password policy includes the requirement that the same password shall not be used across multiple accounts.\n2. The password policy shall clearly state that the same password for accessing systems should not be used for encryption purposes. Different passwords shall be set for each encryption use.\nExample: use of a password generator to manage and generate secure passwords/passphrases.
d183708d-1788-4ac1-9930-8d8303fc88d6	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	21	Healthcare providers shall ensure that each personnel is provided with unique user accounts (i.e., not to be shared) whenever possible	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. To ensure accountability and traceability, organisation shall disallow the sharing of accounts by employees.\n2. Should a shared account be required; organisation shall establish clear and robust processes to ensure that any changes made can be traced and accounted to the individual that has made the changes.
0c6ea040-a031-4711-8cc1-223c506bceba	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	22	User account shall be disabled and / or locked out after multiple failed login attempts, e.g., after 10 failed login attempts.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. To prevent password brute force attacks, user account lockout thresholds shall be configured to lockout after a defined number of failed login attempts.\n2. The defined threshold shall be determined with support from business and operation teams to minimize the impact to operations while balancing security risks.\n3. The defined threshold shall be endorsed by senior management.\nExample:\nDefined threshold = 10 failed login attempts
2c0c95cb-b1fd-40e1-a6f2-077004a3f5fb	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	23	Access shall be managed to ensure third-parties / contractors can access only the information and systems required for their job role. Such access shall be removed once they no longer require them	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisation shall establish a clear access control matrix (UAM) where access rights shall be determined using role-based access rights for all staff and/or third-parties.\nExamples of third-parties:\n- Vendors\n- Contractors\n- Interns\n- Part timers\n2. Organisation shall conduct user access reviews of the UAM on a\nregular basis, such as half yearly.
f68b7883-087a-4de2-b6e1-c4345c60dc9a	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	25	Third-party or contractors working with sensitive information in the healthcare\nprovider shall sign a Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA) form. The form should\ninclude the consequences (e.g. damages) for failure to abide by the agreement	No		No		Sample NDA	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Before commencing any sharing of information (i.e., health information, personal data or organisational sensitive data), a Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA) shall be signed.\n2. The NDA shall include penalties and consequences for noncompliances.\n3. Organisation shall ensure that the coverage of the NDA and Service Level Agreement (SLA) includes adequate protections for the organisation.
6295a3f5-3b33-4770-afaa-ff2ca1dbc8ae	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	26	Physical access control shall be implemented to allow only authorised employees or contractors to access the healthcare provider�s IT assets and/or environment, e.g., use of cable lock to lock the workstations and card access door lock to authenticate and authorise entry.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Physical access to offices and IT systems or assets shall be restricted to only authorized personnel. Vendors that are authorized should be escorted when accessing IT assets and system.\n2. All IT assets such as servers or network switches shall be physically\nsecured . Example: server racks.\n3. Endpoint devices shall be secured physically. Example, secured\nwith cable locks.\nExample of physical access controls are:\na) card access system\nb) bio-metric access.
63bd930b-d1af-41bd-bfdc-c6f58bcac22d	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[3]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Implement access control measures to control access to your data and services	27	The healthcare provider shall maintain log-in rules (i.e., tracking of users logging in and out of systems) properly and review them periodically, and ensure that only authorised individuals have access to security logs.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	3	1. Organisation shall turn on audit trails and security logging to track user activities for systems and applications and review periodically to flag out possible inappropriate accesses.\n2.For organisations that do not have a client / server environment, administrators need to ensure endpoint device logging are turned on.\n3. Only administrators shall have access to the log file.\n4. Log files shall be available upon request (i.e., for incident investigations or upon request by regulators)
13282e02-0fce-4acd-a2ef-93bb55ddf600	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[4]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Secure configuration - Use secure settings for your organisation's procured hardware and software	28	Security configurations shall be implemented for assets, including desktops,\nservers, and routers. This requirement may be met in different ways, e.g., choosing systems with MFA functionality to manage and access patient and corporate information, adopting industry recommendations and standards such as the Centre of Internet Security (CIS) benchmarks on configuration guidelines across multiple vendor products, and running security baseline analyser and system configuration scripts.	No		No		Sample configuration Management Policy from NIST\nConfiguration Management Policy docx.\nSecure Configuration Standard docx.\nCloud Security Guidance From Cloud Securiy Alliance\nGuidelines for System Harvesting	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	4	1. Organisation shall establish a baseline hardening standard.\nExample, from Centre of Internet Security (CIS), Cloud Security Alliance best practices etc.\n2. To enhance the security of systems from the exploitation of vulnerabilities by threat actors, organisation shall review industry standards and consider implementing the standards after taking\noperational needs into consideration.
994adc1d-f6a4-447c-ad90-04db00a20a90	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[4]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Secure configuration - Use secure settings for your organisation's procured hardware and software	29	Weak or default configurations shall be avoided or updated before assets are used, e.g., changing default password and performing a deep scan with an anti- malware solution instead of using a standard scan.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	4	1. Organisation shall review default system configurations and rectify weak settings before deploying the assets, i.e., Organisation shall always change the passwords of default accounts and disable default accounts where possible, to prevent risk of attack using default account and password.\n2. Organisation shall adopt hardening guidelines for system, operating system and devices from industry best practices such as CIS, Cloud Security Alliance, etc.
d2b337a5-e37a-4d70-9842-650b9e0f43cb	56e2b62a-c393-4bcf-ae6d-1b8c4b0fa823	[4]  CYBERSECURITY: Secure / Protect - Secure configuration - Use secure settings for your organisation's procured hardware and software	30	Insecure configurations and weak protocols shall be replaced or upgraded to\naddress the associated vulnerabilities, e.g., using Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure (HTTPS) over normal HTTP to encrypt data communication and upgrading Wired Equivalent Privacy (WEP) to Wi-Fi Protected Access 2/3 (WPA2/WPA3) to enhance the Wi-Fi security standards.	No		No			2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	2025-05-28 22:06:20.840295+00	4	
